            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Yes, I have read `help shell-powershell`. The `minimal.lua` is simply a minimal example for illustration, I did not include `shellredir` and `shellpipe` options since they are irrelevant to this issue.\n\nYou may use the following `minimal.lua`, which keeps the setting mentioned in `:h shell-powershell` unchanged,  and try `:%!xxd` and `:%!xxd;` to see the difference.\n\n```lua\nvim.o.shelltemp = false -- use pipes instead of temp files\n-- These lines are consistent with the setting in `:h shellpowershell`\nif vim.fn.executable(\"pwsh\") then\n    vim.o.shell = \"pwsh\"\nelse\n    vim.o.shell = \"powershell\"\nend\nvim.o.shellcmdflag = [[-NoLogo -NonInteractive -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Command [Console]::InputEncoding=[Console]::OutputEncoding=[System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new();$PSDefaultParameterValues['Out-File:Encoding']='utf8';$PSStyle.OutputRendering='plaintext';Remove-Alias -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue tee;]]\nvim.o.shellredir = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | Out-File %s; exit $LastExitCode'\nvim.o.shellpipe  = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | tee %s; exit $LastExitCode'\nvim.o.shellquote = \"\"\nvim.o.shellxquote = \"\"\n```\n\nBelow is another demo to reproduce this bug with the above `minimal.lua`, using `:read !cat hello.cpp` to read `hello.cpp` to the current buffer, note that in the error log `hello.cpp` is truncated to `hello.cp`, and appending a dummy semicolon bypasses this issue.\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/327c7087-e119-49c7-a869-0af5d4066bea",
